Seeking attention comes from ego, pride, and a need to be seen.

One feeds your ego; the other feeds the room 🙌🏻

I just realized something.
Every single session—I forget to introduce myself.
Not because I don’t want to, but because the moment I walk in, it becomes all about you.

It’s my love language.
I genuinely care.
About your mind. Your body. Your energy. Your story.
About how you show up, move, laugh, push through, and share a piece of who you are with me—through movement.

In a world obsessed with social media, numbers, and popularity, I feel greatful I’m still that same 15-year-old (that’s when I took my first class) who just wants to make people smile
and help them believe they are capable of everything.

If you’ve ever moved with me—you matter.
And I’m so grateful you let me be a part of your journey. ❤️

Never straightened my hair, never blow-dried it, never styled it.
Parlour aunties would give me a standing ovation whenever I walked in — my mother by my side, shedding a small, proud tear because I had finally chosen to groom myself. A rare sight, truly.

As a kid, I was always called a ‘tomboy’.
As an adult… I was just called a charri chokri — stupid, basically (shoutout to the Sindhi aunties).

You never really know how much you love something until it’s gone.
I thought I understood that statement — but God made sure I really felt it this time. :p

So, I decided to take my hair out on the town for one last hurrah — to my friend’s wedding.
Felt like the right way to say goodbye.

And honestly, if you can still feel joy at someone else’s celebration while your own world is quietly unraveling… you’re doing better than you think. That’s joy. That’s resilience. That’s also maybe emotional gymnastics. But hey, we show up — shiny hair and all 💌

Ft @namrata_h @paribajoria @shrestbhargava laugh & support
